Simple Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select more than two attributes that are suitable and create a scatterplot matrix (e.g., with pandas or altair).

df = df_data[['attack', 'defense', 'sp_attack', 'sp_defense']] # Select values to be displayed
pd.plotting.scatter_matrix(
    df, 
    alpha=0.3, # Transparency value for single data point
    figsize=(10, 10) #Increase size
);

Colored Scatterplot Matrix¶

Select a categorical attribute and encode its values with color in the scatterplot matrix (e.g. with altair again or seaborn pairplot).

In [47]:
sns.pairplot( # No need to preselect values here, they are selected by the x/y variable names
    df_data,
    x_vars=['attack', 'defense', 'sp_attack', 'sp_defense'],
    y_vars=['attack', 'defense', 'sp_attack', 'sp_defense'],
    hue='is_legendary' # Highlights points when the pokemon is legendary
);

Interpretation¶

  1. The bigger insight that was gained from the second plot is that legendary pokemon do typically have a higher ration of attack/defense and sp_attack/sp_defense than "normal" pokemon. This can especially be seen in the diagonals that the peak for the legendary pokemon is way more to the right. There are obviously some outliers which do have very low values for all values, yet they are far away from forming a majority. Overall, there are way more "normal" pokemon than legendary pokemon
  2. Most data is cluttered around the center at around 75 points for all data and not clearly linear. However, in the simple scatterplot matrix it can be observed quite well that there is a very direct link between attack and sp_attack as well as between defense and sp_defense as they definitly form some sort of diagonal with the same value for both "normal" and "special" attack values.

Task: Heat Map

Select suitable attributes and visualise the data in a heatmap, e.g. with seaborn or altair.
Do not create a correlation heatmap. Correlations can already be read from the scatterplot matrix.

In [8]:
# First select only needed columns
pok_data = df_data[['generation', 'type1', 'attack']]
# Transform into a pivot table and aggregate the mean of the attack values for each primary type in each generation
pok_data = pd.pivot_table(pok_data, columns=['type1'], index=['generation'], values=['attack'], aggfunc=np.mean, fill_value=0)

sns.set(rc = {'figure.figsize':(12,5)}) # Set larger figure size
ax = sns.heatmap(pok_data, cbar_kws={'label': 'Average attack'}); # Create heatmap and set cbar label
ax.set(xlabel='Primary type', ylabel='Pokemon generation') # Set x label
ax.set_xticklabels(pok_data.columns.get_level_values('type1').to_list()); # Set ticks for xlabel with type names
ax.set_yticklabels(ax.get_yticklabels(), rotation = 0); # Set ylabels to not be rotated 90 degrees
sns.reset_orig(); #Reset figure size to avoid troubles with upcomming charts

Interpretation¶

  1. Pokemon with the primary type flying are hardly present, in total only in Gen5 and Gen6 creatures have this as their primary type and then with rather low average attack in Gen 6. On the opposite, quite a handfull of types have had pokemon as their primary type throughout all of the generations
  2. Primary type dragons have rather high average attack, especially in Gen 3 and Gen 5, not counting their absence in Gen 2. Solid values can be accounted for water and rock type pokemon.

Task: Parallel Coordinates

Select a categorical attribute and encode the lines with color in the parallel coordinates chart. (e.g. with pandas or altair).

In [44]:
# Filter data first, only take fairy and ground type1 pokemon that are not legendary (avoid outliers)
pok_data = df_data[((df_data['type1'] == 'fairy')  | (df_data['type1'] == 'ground')) & (df_data['is_legendary'] == 0)]

# Plot pokemon stats in regards of their (special) attack / defense
par_plot = pd.plotting.parallel_coordinates(
    pok_data,
    'type1', # Attribute for parallel coordinates
    cols=['attack', 'defense', 'sp_attack', 'sp_defense'], # Columns for which the different values are shown
    color=('#A0522D', '#FF69B4') # Color for the axis
);

Interpretation¶

  1. Ground pokemon do typically have rather high attack and defense values compared to fairy type pokemon, although the values are much more spreaded in these two columns. Ground pokemons do have rather low special attack values and also not too high special defense (no wonder, they typically do physical attacks in the games).
  2. Fairy type pokemon put more effort into higher values for special attack and also defense, even though there are some scattered values which are rather low. Overall, the normal attack is quite on the lower side, the defense as well, even though it is a bit better

Additional note: It was rather hard to construct a scenarion which has meaningfull data to show. First I tried to go for the attack some types over the different generations, but this turned out to be very confusing. Also plotting the (special) attack/defense for different types in one generation turned out to be a rather bad idea. Therefore I settled for the comparison of two types in the end with regards to their (special) attack/defense and tried to colour it nicely
